However, in this study, we found that soil nutrient heterogeneity could not alter the intraspecific competition of 
 M. aquaticum. This was not due to an absence of competition, as plants grew less at high than at low density treatments both when soil nutrients were homogeneous and when they were heterogeneous. The reasons for these results may be as follows: First, clonal plants can share resources among individual subunits by physiological integration (
 Hutchings and Wijesinghe, 1997; 
 Hellstrom et al., 2006), which may alleviate the severe competition between individual subunits in nutrient- patches (
 Novoplansky, 2009; 
 Dong et al., 2015). Second, resource heterogeneity can significantly affect plant competition when individuals are not genetically identical (
 Day et al., 2003b; 
 Zhou et al., 2012) or may be due to the differences in plant ability to place foraging organs in areas where available resources are high (
 Wijesinghe et al., 2001; 
 Bliss et al., 2002).
